r-element-3fb9b3c elementor-section-stretched elementor-section-boxed elementor-section-height-default elementor-section-height-default\" data-id=\"3fb9b3c\" data-element_type=\"section\" data-settings=\"{&quot;stretch_section&quot;:&quot;section-stretched&quot;}\">\n\t\t\t\t\t\t<div class=\"elementor-container elementor-column-gap-default\">\n\t\t\t\t\t\t\t<div class=\"elementor-row\">\n\t\t\t\t\t<div class=\"elementor-column elementor-col-100 elementor-top-column elementor-element elementor-element-cc88e83\" data-id=\"cc88e83\" data-element_type=\"column\">\n\t\t\t<div class=\"elementor-column-wrap elementor-element-populated\">\n\t\t\t\t\t\t\t<div class=\"elementor-widget-wrap\">\n\t\t\t\t\t\t<div class=\"elementor-element elementor-element-8fa06ee elementor-widget elementor-widget-heading\" data-id=\"8fa06ee\" data-element_type=\"widget\" data-widget_type=\"heading.default\">\n\t\t\t\t<div class=\"elementor-widget-container\">\n\t\t\t<h2 class=\"elementor-heading-title elementor-size-default\">Phases of Wound Healing<\/h2>\t\t<\/div>\n\t\t\t\t<\/div>\n\t\t\t\t\t\t<\/div>\n\t\t\t\t\t<\/div>\n\t\t<\/div>\n\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t<\/div>\n\t\t\t\t\t<\/div>\n\t\t<\/section>\n\t\t\t\t<section class=\"elementor-section elementor-top-section elementor-element elementor-element-c991400 elementor-section-stretched elementor-section-boxed elementor-section-height-default elementor-section-height-default\" data-id=\"c991400\" data-element_type=\"section\" data-settings=\"{&quot;stretch_section&quot;:&quot;section-stretched&quot;}\">\n\t\t\t\t\t\t<div class=\"elementor-container elementor-column-gap-default\">\n\t\t\t\t\t\t\t<div class=\"elementor-row\">\n\t\t\t\t\t<div class=\"elementor-column elementor-col-100 elementor-top-column elementor-element elementor-element-b748f33\" data-id=\"b748f33\" data-element_type=\"column\">\n\t\t\t<div class=\"elementor-column-wrap elementor-element-populated\">\n\t\t\t\t\t\t\t<div class=\"elementor-widget-wrap\">\n\t\t\t\t\t\t<div class=\"elementor-element elementor-element-e878a96 elementor-widget elementor-widget-text-editor\" data-id=\"e878a96\" data-element_type=\"widget\" data-widget_type=\"text-editor.default\">\n\t\t\t\t<div class=\"elementor-widget-container\">\n\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t<div class=\"elementor-text-editor elementor-clearfix\">\n\t\t\t\t<p><strong>1. Hemostasis<\/strong> <a class=\"button\" style=\"background-color: #193556; padding: 2px 7px; border-radius: 2px;\" href=\"#MN\">Mn <\/a><\/p><ul><li>Timing: Immediate<\/li><li><strong>Vasoconstriction \u2013 First Step<\/strong><\/li><li>Collagen is Exposed &amp; Endothelium Releases Platelet-Activating Factor (PAF)<\/li><li>Platelets Bind Collagen &amp; Form Platelet Plug<\/li><li>Coagulation Cascade Reinforces the Platelet Plug<\/li><\/ul><p><strong>2. Inflammation<\/strong><\/p><ul><li>Timing: Days 1-10<\/li><li>Initiated by Transudate Leakage into Tissues from Injured Blood Vessels<\/li><li>Causes Swelling, Pain, Erythema &amp; Pain<\/li><li>Dominant Cell Types:<ul><li>Day 0-2: <strong>Neutrophils (PMNs)<\/strong> <a class=\"button\" style=\"background-color: #193556; padding: 2px 7px; border-radius: 2px;\" href=\"#MN\">Mn <\/a><\/li><li>Day 3-4: Macrophages #1, Then Lymphocytes<\/li><\/ul><\/li><\/ul><p><strong>3. Proliferation<\/strong><\/p><ul><li>Timing: 5 Days \u2013 3 Weeks<\/li><li>Wound is Rebuilt with New Tissue<\/li><li>Primary Cell Type:<strong> Fibroblasts<\/strong><ul><li>Deposit Collagen &amp; Replace Fibrin<\/li><li>Myofibroblasts \u2013 Cause Wound Contraction<\/li><\/ul><\/li><li>Phases:<ul><li><em>Neovascularization\/Angiogenesis<\/em><ul><li>Growth of New Blood Vessels\/Capillaries into Injured Tissue<\/li><li>Allows Formation of Granulation Tissue<\/li><li>Stimulated By: TGF-\u03b2, TNF-\u03b1, VEGF, PDGF, FGF &amp; Angiogenin<ul><li>Hypoxia is the #1 Stimulator of Angiogenesis<\/li><\/ul><\/li><li>Proteolytic Enzymes are Activated by Endothelial Cells &amp; Dissolve the Basement Membrane<\/li><li>Endothelial Cells Migrate into the Wound Using Integrins<\/li><li>Matrix Metalloproteinases (MMPs) Dissolve Surrounding Tissue to Create a Path<\/li><\/ul><\/li><li><em>Granulation<\/em><ul><li>Well-Vascularized Tissue Covers the Wound Bed to Allow Epithelialization<\/li><li>Healthy Granulation Tissue \u2013 Red\/Pink &amp; Granular\/Uneven in Texture (\u201cCobblestone\u201d-Like)<\/li><li>Dark Granulation Tissue Indicates Ischemia or Infection<\/li><\/ul><\/li><li><em>Epithelialization<\/em><ul><li>Epithelial Cells Cover the Wound Bed<\/li><li>Produced by Keratinocytes<\/li><\/ul><\/li><\/ul><\/li><li>Reopened Wounds Heal Faster the Second Time (Healing Cells Already Present)<\/li><\/ul><p><strong>4. Remodeling (Maturation)<\/strong><\/p><ul><li>Timing: &gt; 3 Weeks<\/li><li>Collagen is Remodeled from Type III to Type I<ul><li>Net Amount of Collagen is Unchanged<\/li><\/ul><\/li><li>Collagen is Also Cross-Linked to Increase Strength &amp; Decrease Scar Thickness<\/li><li>Results in <strong>Scar<\/strong> Formation<\/li><\/ul><p><strong>Tensile Strength<\/strong><\/p><ul><li>Dependent on Collagen Deposition &amp; Cross-Linking<\/li><li>Maximum <strong>Collagen Amount<\/strong> at <strong>3 Weeks<\/strong><ul><li>Mostly Type III \u2013 Then Replaced by Type I &amp; Cross-Linking<\/li><\/ul><\/li><li>Maximum <strong>Strength<\/strong> at <strong>6 Weeks<\/strong><ul><li>Only a <strong>Maximum 80% Total Strength of Original Skin<\/strong><\/li><\/ul><\/li><\/ul>\t\t\t\t\t<\/div>\n\t\t\t\t\t\t<\/div>\n\t\t\t\t<\/div>\n\t\t\t\t\t\t<\/div>\n\t\t\t\t\t<\/div>\n\t\t<\/div>\n\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t<\/div>\n\t\t\t\t\t<\/div>\n\t\t<\/section>\n\t\t\t\t<section class=\"elementor-section elementor-top-section elementor-element elementor-element-0059490 elementor-section-stretched elementor-section-boxed elementor-section-height-default elementor-section-height-default\" data-id=\"0059490\" data-element_type=\"section\" id=\"MN\" data-settings=\"{&quot;stretch_section&quot;:&quot;section-stretched&quot;}\">\n\t\t\t\t\t\t<div class=\"elementor-container elementor-column-gap-default\">\n\t\t\t\t\t\t\t<div class=\"elementor-row\">\n\t\t\t\t\t<div class=\"elementor-column elementor-col-100 elementor-top-column elementor-element elementor-element-2d7e074\" data-id=\"2d7e074\" data-element_type=\"column\">\n\t\t\t<div class=\"elementor-column-wrap elementor-element-populated\">\n\t\t\t\t\t\t\t<div class=\"elementor-widget-wrap\">\n\t\t\t\t\t\t<div class=\"elementor-element elementor-element-654a929 elementor-widget elementor-widget-heading\" data-id=\"654a929\" data-element_type=\"widget\" data-widget_type=\"heading.default\">\n\t\t\t\t<div class=\"elementor-widget-container\">\n\t\t\t<h2 class=\"elementor-heading-title elementor-size-default\">Mnemonics<\/h2>\t\t<\/div>\n\t\t\t\t<\/div>\n\t\t\t\t\t\t<\/div>\n\t\t\t\t\t<\/div>\n\t\t<\/div>\n\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t<\/div>\n\t\t\t\t\t<\/div>\n\t\t<\/section>\n\t\t\t\t<section class=\"elementor-section elementor-top-section elementor-element elementor-element-1b46b0c elementor-section-stretched elementor-section-boxed elementor-section-height-default elementor-section-height-default\" data-id=\"1b46b0c\" data-element_type=\"section\" data-settings=\"{&quot;stretch_section&quot;:&quot;section-stretched&quot;}\">\n\t\t\t\t\t\t<div class=\"elementor-container elementor-column-gap-default\">\n\t\t\t\t\t\t\t<div class=\"elementor-row\">\n\t\t\t\t\t<div class=\"elementor-column elementor-col-100 elementor-top-column elementor-element elementor-element-553117b\" data-id=\"553117b\" data-element_type=\"column\">\n\t\t\t<div class=\"elementor-column-wrap elementor-element-populated\">\n\t\t\t\t\t\t\t<div class=\"elementor-widget-wrap\">\n\t\t\t\t\t\t<div class=\"elementor-element elementor-element-410f601 elementor-widget elementor-widget-text-editor\" data-id=\"410f601\" data-element_type=\"widget\" data-widget_type=\"text-editor.default\">\n\t\t\t\t<div class=\"elementor-widget-container\">\n\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t<div class=\"elementor-text-editor elementor-clearfix\">\n\t\t\t\t<p><strong>Phases of Wound Healing<\/strong><\/p><ul><li>Healing Wounds are HIPR (Hyper)<ul><li>1. Hemostasis<\/li><li>2. Inflammation<\/li><li>3. Proliferation<\/li><li>4. Remodeling<\/li><\/ul><\/li><\/ul><p><strong>Order of Cell Arrival in a Healing Wound<\/strong><\/p><ul><li>Think P.O.N.M.L. (Reverse of L.M.N.O.P.)<\/li><li>Platelets (#1) &gt; 0-Skip &gt; Neutrophils &gt; Macrophages &gt; Lymphocytes<\/li><\/ul>\t\t\t\t\t<\/div>\n\t\t\t\t\t\t<\/div>\n\t\t\t\t<\/div>\n\t\t\t\t\t\t<\/div>\n\t\t\t\t\t<\/div>\n\t\t<\/div>\n\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t<\/div>\n\t\t\t\t\t<\/div>\n\t\t<\/section>\n\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t<\/div>\n\t\t\t<\/div>\n\t\t\t\t\t<\/div>\n\t\t","protected":false},"excerpt":{"rendered":"<p>Wound Care: Phases of Wound Healing Phases of Wound Healing 1. Hemostasis Mn Timing: Immediate Vasoconstriction \u2013 First Step Collagen is Exposed &amp; Endothelium Releases Platelet-Activating Factor (PAF) Platelets Bind Collagen &amp; Form Platelet Plug Coagulation Cascade Reinforces the Platelet Plug 2. Inflammation Timing: Days 1-10 Initiated by Transudate Leakage into Tissues from Injured Blood [&hellip;]<\/p>\n","protected":false},"author":1,"featured_media":0,"parent":0,"menu_order":0,"comment_status":"closed","ping_status":"closed","template":"","meta":{"_mi_skip_tracking":false},"folder":[36],"_links":{"self":[{"href":"https:\/\/operativereview.com\/wp-json\/wp\/v2\/pages\/7243"}],"collection":[{"href":"https:\/\/operativereview.com\/wp-json\/wp\/v2\/pages"}],"about":[{"href":"https:\/\/operativereview.com\/wp-json\/wp\/v2\/types\/page"}],"author":[{"embeddable":true,"href":"https:\/\/operativereview.com\/wp-json\/wp\/v2\/users\/1"}],"replies":[{"embeddable":true,"href":"https:\/\/operativereview.com\/wp-json\/wp\/v2\/comments?post=7243"}],"version-history":[{"count":5,"href":"https:\/\/operativereview.com\/wp-json\/wp\/v2\/pages\/7243\/revisions"}],"predecessor-version":[{"id":14372,"href":"https:\/\/operativereview.com\/wp-json\/wp